WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.860
Oxford Bookworm Stage 1. One Way Ticket by Jennifer Bassett. Published and copyright, Oxford

00:11.860 --> 00:25.340
University Press 1992. The Girl with Green Eyes. Of course, the man in the brown hat said,

00:25.340 --> 00:30.400
there are good policemen and there are bad policemen, you know.

00:30.400 --> 00:40.960
You're right, the young man said. Yes, that's very true. Isn't it, Julie? He looked at the

00:40.960 --> 00:49.240
young woman next to him. Julie didn't answer and looked bored. She closed her eyes.

00:49.240 --> 00:57.520
Julie's my wife. The young man told the man in the brown hat. She doesn't like trains.

00:57.520 --> 01:08.640
She always feels ill on trains. Oh yes, the man in the brown hat said, now my wife, she

01:08.640 --> 01:18.080
doesn't like buses. She nearly had an accident on a bus once. It was last year. No, no,

01:18.080 --> 01:27.640
it wasn't. It was two years ago. I remember now. It was in Manchester. He told a long,

01:27.640 --> 01:38.040
boring story about his wife and a bus in Manchester. It was a hot day and the train was slow.

01:38.040 --> 01:45.040
There were seven people in the carriage. There was the man in the brown hat, the young man

01:45.040 --> 01:55.280
and his wife, Julie, a mother and two children and a tall, dark man in an expensive suit.

01:55.280 --> 02:04.640
The young man's name was Bill. He had short brown hair and a happy smile. His wife, Julie,

02:04.640 --> 02:12.840
had long red hair and very green eyes. The colour of sea water. They were very beautiful

02:12.920 --> 02:23.520
eyes. The man in the brown hat talked and talked. He had a big red face and a loud voice. He

02:23.520 --> 02:31.680
talked to Bill because Bill liked to talk too. The man in the brown hat laughed a lot and when

02:31.680 --> 02:41.080
he laughed, Bill laughed too. Bill liked talking and laughing with people. The two children were

02:41.080 --> 02:49.320
hot and bored. They didn't want to sit down. They wanted to be noisy and run up and down the

02:49.320 --> 02:59.560
train. Now sit down and be quiet, their mother said. She was a small woman with a tired face

02:59.560 --> 03:01.200
and a tired voice.

03:01.200 --> 03:14.760
I don't want to sit down, the little boy said. I'm thirsty. Here, have an orange, his mother said.

03:14.760 --> 03:25.120
She took an orange out of her bag and gave it to him. I want an orange too, the little girl said

03:25.120 --> 03:36.720
loudly. All right. Here you are, said her mother. Eat it nicely now. The children ate their oranges

03:36.720 --> 03:49.000
and were quiet for a minute. Then the little boy said, I want a drink. I'm thirsty. The tall,

03:49.000 --> 03:58.040
dark man took out his newspaper and began to read. Julie opened her eyes and looked at the

03:58.040 --> 04:05.800
back page of his newspaper. She read about the weather in Budapest and about the football in

04:05.800 --> 04:14.440
Liverpool. She wasn't interested in Budapest and she didn't like football, but she didn't want to

04:14.440 --> 04:24.560
listen to Bill and the man in the brown hat. Talk, talk, talk, she thought. Bill never stops talking.

04:24.560 --> 04:35.880
Then suddenly she saw the tall man's eyes over the top of his newspaper. She could not see his mouth,

04:35.960 --> 04:45.040
but there was a smile in his eyes. Quickly she looked down at the newspaper and read about the

04:45.040 --> 04:53.560
weather in Budapest again. The train stopped at Dourlish Station and people got on and got off.

04:53.560 --> 05:04.640
There was a lot of noise. Is this our station? The little girl asked. She went to the window and

05:04.640 --> 05:11.480
looked out. No, it isn't. Now sit down, her mother said.

05:11.480 --> 05:24.960
We're going to Penzance, the little girl told Bill, for our holidays. Yes, her mother said. My

05:24.960 --> 05:35.240
sister's got a little hotel by the sea. We're staying there. It's cheap, you see. Yes, the man

05:35.240 --> 05:44.680
in the brown hat said, it's a nice town. I know a man there. He's got a restaurant in King Street.

05:45.680 --> 05:54.080
A lot of holiday people go there. He makes a lot of money in the summer. He laughed loudly.

05:54.080 --> 06:00.320
Yes, he said again. You can have a nice holiday in Penzance.

06:00.320 --> 06:12.720
We're going to St. Ostal, Bill said. Me and Julie, it's our first holiday. Julie wanted to go to Spain,

06:12.720 --> 06:22.480
but I like St. Ostal. I always go there for my holidays. It's nice in August. You can have a

06:22.480 --> 06:34.560
good time there too. Julie looked out of the window. Where is Budapest? She thought. I want to go there.

06:35.440 --> 06:48.080
I want to go to Vienna, to Paris, to Rome, to Athens. Her green eyes were bored and angry. Through

06:48.080 --> 06:56.040
the window she watched the little villages and hills of England. The man in the brown hat looked

06:56.040 --> 07:04.120
at Julie. You're right, he said to Bill. You can have a good time on holiday in England.

07:04.120 --> 07:14.040
We always go to Brighton, me and the wife. But the weather, we went one year and it rained

07:14.440 --> 07:25.800
every day, morning, afternoon and night. It's true, it never stopped raining. He laughed loudly.

07:26.680 --> 07:31.720
We nearly went home after the first week. Bill laughed too.

07:33.160 --> 07:41.400
What did you do all day then? He asked. Julie read about the weather in Budapest for the third time.

07:42.280 --> 07:50.680
Then she looked at the tall man's hands. They were long, brown hands, very clean.

07:50.680 --> 07:58.440
Nice hands, she thought. He wore a very expensive Japanese watch.

07:58.440 --> 08:09.800
Japan, she thought. I'd like to go to Japan. She looked up and saw the man's eyes again over

08:09.800 --> 08:19.960
the top of his newspaper. This time she did not look away. Green eyes looked into dark brown eyes

08:19.960 --> 08:30.440
for a long, slow minute. After Newton Abbott's station, the guard came into the carriage to

08:30.440 --> 08:37.320
look at their tickets. Now then, he said, where are we all going?

08:39.880 --> 08:48.280
This trains late, the man in the brown hat said. 20 minutes late by my watch.

08:48.760 --> 09:01.160
10 minutes, the guard said. That's all. He smiled at Julie. The tall, dark man put his newspaper down,

09:01.160 --> 09:07.960
found his ticket, and gave it to the guard. The guard looked at it.

09:08.920 --> 09:18.520
You're all right, sir. He said. The boat doesn't leave Plymouth before six o'clock. You got lots of time.

09:18.520 --> 09:27.000
The tall man smiled, put his ticket back in his pocket, and opened his newspaper again.

09:27.480 --> 09:38.600
Julie didn't look at him. A boat, she thought. He's taking a boat from Plymouth. Where's he going?

09:38.600 --> 09:48.520
She looked at him again with her long green eyes. He read his newspaper and didn't look at her,

09:49.160 --> 09:59.080
but his eyes smiled. The train stopped at Tottenham's station, and more people got on and off.

09:59.080 --> 10:11.960
Everybody's going on holiday, Bill said. He laughed. It's going to be wonderful. No work for two weeks.

10:12.920 --> 10:20.680
It's a nice, quiet town, St. Ostal. We can stay in bed in the mornings, and sit and talk in the

10:20.680 --> 10:27.880
afternoons, and have a drink or two in the evenings. Hey, Julie. He looked at his wife.

10:29.320 --> 10:36.760
Are you all right, Julie? Yes, Bill. She said quietly. I'm okay.

10:36.760 --> 10:44.920
She looked out of the window again. The train went more quickly now, and it began to rain.

10:44.920 --> 10:55.640
Bill and the man in the brown hat talked and talked. Bill told a long story about two men and a dog,

10:55.640 --> 11:05.320
and the man in the brown hat laughed very loudly. That's a good story, he said. I like that.

11:06.280 --> 11:15.160
You tell it very well. Do you know the story about, and he told Bill a story about a Frenchman

11:15.160 --> 11:24.920
and a bicycle? Why do people laugh at these stories, Julie thought? They're so boring,

11:26.600 --> 11:35.160
but Bill liked it. Then he told a story about an old woman and a cat, and the man in the brown

11:35.640 --> 11:44.680
hat laughed again. That's good, too. I don't know. How do you remember them all?

11:46.440 --> 11:51.480
Because, Julie thought, he tells them every day.

11:53.800 --> 11:59.720
I don't understand. The little girl said suddenly. She looked at Bill.

12:00.040 --> 12:03.080
Why did the cat die?

12:04.840 --> 12:11.320
Shh. Be quiet, her mother said. Come and eat your sandwiches now.

12:13.320 --> 12:22.120
That's all right, Bill said. I like children. The man in the brown hat looked at the children's

12:22.120 --> 12:22.840
sandwiches.

12:24.520 --> 12:33.160
Mmm. I'm hungry, too. He said. You can get sandwiches in the restaurant on this train.

12:34.200 --> 12:40.520
He looked at Bill. Let's go down to the restaurant, eh? I need a drink, too.

12:42.600 --> 12:48.200
Bill laughed. You're right. It's thirsty work telling stories.

12:48.680 --> 12:57.080
The two men stood up and left the carriage. The little girl ate her sandwich and looked at Julie.

12:57.960 --> 13:05.240
But why did the cat die? She asked. I don't know, Julie said.

13:05.880 --> 13:12.360
Perhaps it wanted to die. The little girl came and sat next to Julie.

13:12.600 --> 13:18.040
I like your hair, she said. It's beautiful.

13:19.240 --> 13:21.880
Julie looked down at her and smiled.

13:23.240 --> 13:26.440
For some minutes, it was quiet in the carriage.

13:27.720 --> 13:32.680
Then the tall, dark man opened his bag and took out a book.

13:33.960 --> 13:38.520
He put it on the seat next to him and looked at Julie with a smile.

13:38.520 --> 13:44.520
Julie looked back at him and then down at the book.

13:45.960 --> 13:53.800
Famous towns of Italy, she read. Venice, Florence, Rome, Naples.

13:55.320 --> 13:58.680
She looked away again out of the window at the rain.

14:00.200 --> 14:06.360
Two weeks in St. Oster, she thought, with Bill, in the rain.

14:08.680 --> 14:12.760
After half an hour, the two men came back to the carriage.

14:13.960 --> 14:19.960
There are a lot of people on this train, Bill said. Do you want a sandwich, Julie?

14:21.400 --> 14:26.120
No, she said. I'm not hungry. You eat them.

14:28.200 --> 14:34.200
The train was nearly at Plymouth. Doors opened and people began to move.

14:35.080 --> 14:40.280
A lot of people get on here, the man in the brown hat said.

14:41.880 --> 14:47.800
The tall, dark man stood up and put his book and his newspaper in his bag.

14:48.920 --> 14:52.040
Then he picked up his bag and left the carriage.

14:53.240 --> 14:55.400
The train stopped at the station.

14:56.600 --> 15:02.760
A lot of people got on the train and two women and an old man came into the carriage.

15:03.640 --> 15:05.640
They had a lot of bags with them.

15:07.080 --> 15:11.480
Bill and the man in the brown hat stood up and helped them.

15:12.840 --> 15:15.800
One of the women had a big bag of apples.

15:17.080 --> 15:21.320
The bag broke and the apples went all over the carriage.

15:22.520 --> 15:23.960
Oh, damn!

15:24.760 --> 15:26.760
She said.

15:26.760 --> 15:30.760
Everybody laughed and helped her to find the apples.

15:31.640 --> 15:34.840
The train moved away from Plymouth Station.

15:36.840 --> 15:43.800
After a minute or two, everybody sat down and the woman gave some apples to the children.

15:46.360 --> 15:51.480
Where's Julie? Bill said suddenly. She's not here.

15:53.400 --> 15:58.040
Perhaps she went to the restaurant. The man in the brown hat said.

15:58.040 --> 16:03.880
But she wasn't hungry, Bill said. She told me.

16:05.880 --> 16:07.800
The little girl looked at Bill.

16:09.640 --> 16:13.000
She got off the train at Plymouth, she said.

16:13.720 --> 16:16.600
With the tall, dark man, I saw them.

16:18.040 --> 16:24.440
Of course she didn't, Bill said. She's on this train. She didn't get off.

16:25.240 --> 16:29.480
Yes, she did. The children's mother said suddenly.

16:30.520 --> 16:35.560
I saw her too. The tall man waited for her on the platform.

16:37.480 --> 16:42.040
He waited for her. Bill's mouth was open.

16:43.000 --> 16:47.560
But he read his newspaper all the time.

16:48.600 --> 16:52.600
He didn't talk to Julie and she never talked to him.

16:53.560 --> 16:55.560
They didn't say a word.

16:56.920 --> 17:02.360
People don't always need words, young man, the children's mother said.

17:03.960 --> 17:05.960
But she's my wife.

17:06.760 --> 17:09.320
Bill's face was red and angry.

17:10.200 --> 17:11.800
She can't do that.

17:12.680 --> 17:15.480
He said loudly. He stood up.

17:16.520 --> 17:18.440
I'm going to stop the train.

17:19.240 --> 17:23.240
Everybody looked at him and the two children laughed.

17:24.120 --> 17:27.320
No, the man in the brown hat said.

17:28.120 --> 17:30.440
No, you don't want to do that.

17:31.320 --> 17:35.080
Sit down and eat your sandwiches, my friend.

17:36.760 --> 17:38.520
But I don't understand.

17:39.480 --> 17:41.080
Why did she go?

17:41.960 --> 17:43.720
What am I going to do?

17:44.440 --> 17:47.640
Bill's face was very unhappy.

17:48.120 --> 17:51.960
After a second or two, he sat down again.

17:53.160 --> 17:55.480
What am I going to do?

17:56.280 --> 17:57.480
He said again.

17:59.080 --> 18:00.120
Nothing.

18:01.080 --> 18:02.920
The man in the brown hat said.

18:03.800 --> 18:05.880
He ate his sandwich slowly.

18:07.080 --> 18:10.280
Go and have your holiday in St. Austin.

18:10.520 --> 18:12.520
You can have a good time there.

18:13.320 --> 18:15.320
Forget about Julie.

18:15.960 --> 18:17.960
Those green eyes now.

18:19.400 --> 18:23.160
He took out a second sandwich and began to eat it.

18:24.120 --> 18:27.160
I knew a woman once with green eyes.

18:28.120 --> 18:30.920
She gave me a very bad time.

18:32.360 --> 18:36.360
No, you want to forget about Julie.

18:41.000 --> 18:43.000
No, you don't want to forget about her.

18:48.440 --> 18:49.880
South for the winter.

18:52.360 --> 18:55.960
I never stay in one country for a long time.

18:56.920 --> 18:58.120
It gets boring.

18:59.560 --> 19:04.840
I like to move on, see new places, meet different people.

19:06.200 --> 19:08.840
It's a good life most of the time.

19:10.600 --> 19:13.400
When I need money, I get a job.

19:14.760 --> 19:16.280
I can do most things.

19:17.400 --> 19:22.360
Hotel and restaurant work, building work, picking fruit.

19:23.800 --> 19:27.320
In Europe, you can pick fruit most of the year.

19:28.840 --> 19:32.760
You need to be in the right country at the right time, of course.

19:34.040 --> 19:37.640
It's not easy work, but the money's not bad.

19:38.440 --> 19:40.920
I like to go south in the winter.

19:41.960 --> 19:48.840
Life is easier in the sun, and Northern Europe can get very cold in the winter.

19:50.040 --> 19:57.080
Last year, 1989, it was, I was in Venice for October.

19:58.280 --> 20:01.800
I did some work in a hotel for three weeks.

20:02.680 --> 20:05.720
Then I began slowly to move south.

20:08.440 --> 20:11.080
I always go by train when I can.

20:12.200 --> 20:13.480
I like trains.

20:14.920 --> 20:19.400
You can walk about on a train, and you meet a lot of people.

20:21.640 --> 20:24.680
I left Venice and went on to Trieste.

20:25.960 --> 20:32.680
There, I got a cheap ticket for the slow train to Sofia in Bulgaria.

20:33.480 --> 20:39.480
This train goes all down through Yugoslavia, and takes a long time,

20:40.120 --> 20:43.880
a day and a half, but that didn't matter to me.

20:46.200 --> 20:50.680
The train left Trieste at nine o'clock on a Thursday morning.

20:51.880 --> 20:57.560
There weren't many people on it at first, but at Zagreb, more people got on.

20:57.640 --> 21:02.680
Two girls went along the corridor, past my carriage.

21:03.480 --> 21:07.480
They looked through the door, but they didn't come in.

21:08.680 --> 21:13.880
Then an old woman came in, sat down, and went to sleep.

21:14.920 --> 21:20.760
The two girls came back along the corridor, and looked into the carriage again.

21:22.200 --> 21:26.760
The train left Zagreb, and I looked out of the window,

21:27.560 --> 21:31.400
for about ten minutes. Then I went to sleep, too.

21:33.880 --> 21:38.520
When I opened my eyes again, the two girls were in the carriage.

21:39.880 --> 21:42.840
They looked friendly, so I said, hello.

21:44.120 --> 21:45.480
Hi, they said.

21:46.840 --> 21:48.600
You're American, I said.

21:49.240 --> 21:51.000
Or Canadian, right?

21:52.120 --> 21:54.760
American, the taller girl said.

21:55.720 --> 21:56.520
She smiled.

21:57.640 --> 21:59.400
And you're 23.

22:00.600 --> 22:02.600
Your name's Tom Walsh.

22:03.720 --> 22:05.160
You've got blue eyes.

22:06.200 --> 22:11.000
And your mum lives in Burnham on C.U.K., right?

22:12.280 --> 22:14.520
How did you know all that, I asked?

22:15.880 --> 22:17.320
The second girl laughed.

22:18.680 --> 22:20.520
She looked at your passport.

22:21.480 --> 22:22.920
It's in your coat pocket.

22:23.880 --> 22:25.000
Oh, right.

22:26.440 --> 22:29.000
My coat was on the seat next to me.

22:30.360 --> 22:35.400
I took my passport out of my pocket, and put it back in my bag.

22:37.000 --> 22:38.920
Who are you then? I asked.

22:40.120 --> 22:40.920
They told me.

22:42.200 --> 22:46.280
Melanie and Carol from Los Angeles, USA.

22:47.720 --> 22:49.400
They liked Europe, they said.

22:50.120 --> 23:06.040
They knew a lot of places, Britain, Holland, Denmark, Germany, France, Spain, Italy, Yugoslavia, Bulgaria, Greece.

23:07.720 --> 23:12.120
I'm going to Bulgaria now, I said, for about a month.

23:13.320 --> 23:15.480
Then I'm going south for the winter.

23:16.360 --> 23:18.920
Cyprus, or perhaps North Africa.

23:20.120 --> 23:21.720
Oh, yes, they said.

23:22.440 --> 23:24.120
We love Bulgaria.

23:24.920 --> 23:27.000
Sophia's a great town.

23:27.000 --> 23:27.560
Wonderful.

23:29.080 --> 23:31.800
What do you do about money, I asked?

23:32.760 --> 23:35.880
Well, you know, Carol smiled.

23:37.000 --> 23:39.480
Sometimes we get a little job.

23:40.360 --> 23:41.160
This and that.

23:42.200 --> 23:43.160
But what about you?

23:44.680 --> 23:45.960
Yeah, come on.

23:46.760 --> 23:47.480
Melanie said.

23:48.600 --> 23:55.160
Tell us about you, Tom Walsh, with the blue eyes, and the mom and burner man sea.

23:56.440 --> 23:58.440
What are you doing with your life, hey?

23:59.960 --> 24:00.920
So I told them.

24:01.800 --> 24:02.920
They were nice girls.

24:04.040 --> 24:09.960
They were older than me, perhaps 27 or 28, but I liked them.

24:10.920 --> 24:13.000
We talked and laughed for hours.

24:13.800 --> 24:17.000
I told them a lot of stories about my life.

24:17.960 --> 24:24.200
Some of the stories were true, some weren't, but the girls laughed and said,

24:24.200 --> 24:25.880
I was a great guy.

24:26.840 --> 24:31.160
I asked them about Bulgaria, because I didn't know the country.

24:32.200 --> 24:34.760
They knew Sophia well, they said.

24:36.120 --> 24:37.240
Hey, Carol.

24:37.640 --> 24:38.440
Melanie said.

24:39.320 --> 24:42.840
We're staying in Bela Palanca for a day or two.

24:43.400 --> 24:48.360
But let's go over to Sophia this weekend and meet Tom there.

24:49.160 --> 24:53.800
We can meet him on Saturday night at the hotel Marmora.

24:55.160 --> 24:59.080
Yeah, it's a good hotel, Carol told me.

24:59.080 --> 25:01.080
Cheap, but good.

25:01.960 --> 25:03.400
Why do you think, Tom?

25:04.040 --> 25:05.400
Great, I said.

25:05.400 --> 25:06.440
Let's do that.

25:07.080 --> 25:07.880
Let's do that.

25:09.640 --> 25:11.480
The train was very slow.

25:13.320 --> 25:18.760
We got to Belgrade at six o'clock in the evening and a lot of people got off.

25:20.040 --> 25:23.320
They were only me and the girls in the carriage then.

25:25.000 --> 25:28.760
The guard came and looked at our tickets and went away again.

25:30.840 --> 25:32.200
Carol looked at Melanie.

25:33.080 --> 25:35.800
Hey, Mel, she said.

25:36.920 --> 25:41.000
Why don't you and Tom go along to the restaurant?

25:41.880 --> 25:45.400
I'm not hungry, and I want to sleep for an hour.

25:46.520 --> 25:51.240
Uh, food's very expensive on the train, I said.

25:52.280 --> 25:54.520
I haven't got much money just now.

25:55.320 --> 25:57.640
I'm going to get a job in Sophia.

25:58.680 --> 26:01.160
Oh, Tom, Melanie said.

26:02.040 --> 26:03.480
Why didn't you tell us?

26:04.760 --> 26:07.480
Look, you're a nice guy, right?

26:08.360 --> 26:10.360
We're okay for money this week.

26:11.160 --> 26:12.520
We can buy you a meal?

26:13.640 --> 26:16.280
Of course we can, Carol said.

26:17.080 --> 26:22.840
And look, in Sophia, we can take you to the best restaurant in town.

26:23.400 --> 26:25.000
It's a great place.

26:25.000 --> 26:25.720
We love it.

26:27.000 --> 26:27.960
What could I say?

26:28.760 --> 26:32.200
I was hungry, they had money, I didn't.

26:34.040 --> 26:37.480
So Melanie and I went to the restaurant and had a meal.

26:39.160 --> 26:43.160
When we came back, Carol was still alone in the carriage.

26:44.520 --> 26:47.640
Melanie put her feet on the seat and went to sleep.

26:49.240 --> 26:52.600
At Niss, some more people got on the train

26:53.240 --> 26:55.800
and two old men came into our carriage.

26:55.880 --> 27:01.320
They looked at Melanie's feet on the seat and talked in loud voices.

27:01.320 --> 27:06.920
Carol laughed, and Melanie opened her eyes and set up.

27:07.960 --> 27:10.200
Are we nearly there?

27:10.200 --> 27:13.880
She asked Carol and looked out of the window.

27:13.880 --> 27:17.640
Yeah, about half an hour, I think.

27:18.840 --> 27:23.080
Why are you getting off at Bela Palanca, I asked.

27:23.160 --> 27:26.040
I asked, what are you going to do there?

27:27.400 --> 27:28.440
Melanie smiled.

27:29.640 --> 27:35.400
Find a cheap hotel, meet people, take a look at the town, you know.

27:36.680 --> 27:41.400
Just for a day or two, Carol said, but there's nothing there.

27:42.520 --> 27:46.200
Oh, well, you never know, Melanie laughed.

27:47.400 --> 27:49.000
See you in Sophia, right?

27:49.720 --> 27:50.920
On Saturday night.

27:51.800 --> 27:54.680
The hotel, Marmara, okay?

27:55.240 --> 27:57.480
Eight o'clock, Carol said.

27:57.480 --> 27:59.160
Don't forget now.

27:59.960 --> 28:02.120
Okay, great, I said.

28:02.120 --> 28:03.320
See you there.

28:05.080 --> 28:08.280
The train came into Bela Palanca and stopped.

28:09.240 --> 28:12.520
The two girls got off and stood on the platform.

28:13.480 --> 28:15.560
They smiled at me through the window.

28:16.360 --> 28:20.200
Saturday, eight o'clock, Melanie shouted.

28:21.720 --> 28:23.160
Okay, I called.

28:24.360 --> 28:27.560
They couldn't hear me because of the noise in the station.

28:28.920 --> 28:33.000
They smiled again, picked up their bags and walked away.

28:34.280 --> 28:35.080
Nice girls.

28:36.120 --> 28:40.040
I'm going to have a great time in Sophia, I thought.

28:44.120 --> 28:49.720
The train left Yugoslavia and crossed into Bulgaria at two o'clock in the morning.

28:50.680 --> 28:52.920
Then the train stopped at some village.

28:53.640 --> 28:55.000
I don't remember the name.

28:56.280 --> 28:58.840
I ate an apple and looked out of the window.

29:00.280 --> 29:03.880
Suddenly, there were a lot of policemen on the train.

29:05.160 --> 29:08.360
Everybody in the carriage sat up and began to talk.

29:10.040 --> 29:10.920
What's happening?

29:11.640 --> 29:14.440
I said in Italian to the old man next to me.

29:15.640 --> 29:16.760
I don't know.

29:17.400 --> 29:19.080
He said in bad Italian.

29:19.800 --> 29:22.120
Perhaps they're looking for somebody.

29:23.080 --> 29:27.960
Look, the police are taking some people off the train.

29:29.720 --> 29:32.600
Then two policemen came into our carriage,

29:33.480 --> 29:36.760
a tall thin one and a short fat one.

29:38.120 --> 29:40.200
They looked at everybody carefully.

29:41.720 --> 29:43.640
And then they looked at me again.

29:45.560 --> 29:46.920
Come with us, please.

29:47.800 --> 29:49.960
The fat policeman said in English.

29:51.000 --> 29:53.160
What? Me? I said.

29:54.040 --> 29:55.800
Why? What's the matter?

29:56.760 --> 30:01.480
And bring your bag with you, the tall policeman said.

30:03.160 --> 30:05.160
I began to ask a question,

30:06.120 --> 30:10.280
but policemen never like questions from young men with long hair.

30:11.400 --> 30:16.360
So I stayed quiet, picked up my bag and went with them.

30:17.720 --> 30:21.960
In the station building, there were a lot more policemen

30:22.600 --> 30:24.440
and some people from the train.

30:25.800 --> 30:28.280
They were all young people I saw.

30:29.480 --> 30:32.280
Some were afraid, some were bored.

30:33.640 --> 30:36.200
The police looked in everybody's bags

30:37.000 --> 30:39.320
and then the people went back to the train.

30:41.240 --> 30:43.880
My two policemen took me to a table.

30:44.840 --> 30:46.680
Your passport, please.

30:47.400 --> 30:48.920
The fat policeman said,

30:49.640 --> 30:50.840
and opened your bag.

30:52.680 --> 30:56.520
They looked at my passport and I opened my bag.

30:58.040 --> 31:02.120
There was a young police woman with red hair at the next table.

31:03.320 --> 31:04.760
She had a nice face,

31:05.400 --> 31:08.360
so I smiled at her and she smiled back.

31:09.720 --> 31:10.440
Ah ha!

31:11.320 --> 31:13.480
The tall policeman said suddenly.

31:14.840 --> 31:18.920
All my dirty shirts and clothes were out on the table.

31:20.200 --> 31:23.960
The policeman picked up my bag and turned it over.

31:25.400 --> 31:34.520
Onto the table, out of my bag, fell packet after packet of US American dollars.

31:35.640 --> 31:37.720
Nice new dollars.

31:38.520 --> 31:41.560
Fifty dollar notes in big packets.

31:42.600 --> 31:43.880
A lot of money.

31:45.800 --> 31:48.760
My mouth opened and stayed open.

31:49.720 --> 31:51.480
I couldn't find my voice.

31:52.920 --> 31:56.600
I was suddenly a very interesting person

31:57.400 --> 32:02.120
and a lot of police ran up to our table and stood behind me.

32:03.000 --> 32:10.040
Fifty thousand, a hundred thousand, a hundred and fifty thousand.

32:11.000 --> 32:16.600
There's two hundred thousand dollars here, the tall policeman said.

32:17.480 --> 32:22.360
What an interesting bag, Mr. Tom Warsh.

32:23.640 --> 32:26.200
I found my voice again quickly.

32:27.080 --> 32:30.040
But it's not my bag, I shouted.

32:30.840 --> 32:35.480
There was a big, happy smile on that policeman's face.

32:35.960 --> 32:40.760
Well, he said, it's got your name on it.

32:40.760 --> 32:41.480
Look!

32:42.440 --> 32:43.800
So I looked.

32:44.440 --> 32:47.240
And of course, there was my name.

32:47.800 --> 32:50.840
And yes, of course, it was my bag.

32:52.120 --> 32:57.480
So how did two hundred thousand US dollars get into my bag?

32:58.200 --> 33:04.600
You cannot bring a US dollars into this country, the fat policeman said.

33:05.800 --> 33:09.880
He had very short gray hair and little black eyes.

33:10.600 --> 33:12.360
He didn't smile once.

33:13.320 --> 33:17.000
But I didn't bring them, I said quickly.

33:17.560 --> 33:19.480
They're not my dollars.

33:20.120 --> 33:27.320
I never saw them before in my life and there was a lot of noise in my life.

33:27.480 --> 33:33.000
I looked out of the window and saw my train.

33:34.040 --> 33:36.520
Slowly, it began to move.

33:37.320 --> 33:40.280
Hey, I shouted, that's my train.

33:41.720 --> 33:43.640
The tall policeman laughed.

33:44.600 --> 33:46.520
It was a great day for him.

33:47.640 --> 33:52.840
Oh no, he said, you're not getting back on that train.

33:53.800 --> 33:59.480
You're staying here with us in our beautiful country.

34:00.680 --> 34:02.200
He smiled happily.

34:03.960 --> 34:07.800
So, I never got to Sophia on Saturday.

34:08.760 --> 34:10.920
I was very unhappy about that.

34:12.040 --> 34:16.040
I wanted to have a little talk with Melanie and Carol.

34:16.840 --> 34:19.640
Ask them one or two questions, you know.

34:20.600 --> 34:22.760
You're a nice guy, Tom.

34:23.400 --> 34:25.480
See you in Sophia, okay?

34:26.280 --> 34:29.160
Take you to the best restaurant in town.

34:29.720 --> 34:31.320
Yeah, great.

34:32.760 --> 34:37.560
And I never got down to Cyprus or North Africa that winter.

34:38.440 --> 34:41.080
Oh well, I live and learn.

34:42.440 --> 34:45.000
It's not an easy life in prison,

34:45.960 --> 34:47.880
but it's warm in winter.

34:48.600 --> 34:49.960
And the food's not bad.

34:51.480 --> 34:53.880
And I'm meeting some interesting people.

34:55.320 --> 34:58.520
There's a man from Georgia, USSR.

34:59.480 --> 35:00.760
Boris, his name is.

35:01.720 --> 35:04.120
He comes from a place by the Black Sea.

35:05.080 --> 35:06.360
He's a great guy.

35:07.480 --> 35:09.000
When we get out of here,

35:09.560 --> 35:11.960
he and I are going down to Australia.

35:12.840 --> 35:15.000
Brisbane, perhaps, or Sydney.

35:15.800 --> 35:17.560
Get a job on a ship.

35:18.360 --> 35:19.720
Start a new life.

35:20.920 --> 35:25.000
Yeah, next year's going to be okay.

35:36.120 --> 35:38.200
Mr. Harris and the Night Train.

35:40.760 --> 35:42.520
Mr. Harris, like trains,

35:43.160 --> 35:46.440
he was afraid of airplanes and didn't like buses.

35:47.160 --> 35:51.160
But trains, they were big and noisy and exciting.

35:52.680 --> 35:55.160
When he was a boy of 10, he liked trains.

35:55.880 --> 35:59.320
Now he was a man of 50, and he still liked trains.

36:00.920 --> 36:04.600
So he was a happy man on the night of the 14th of September.

36:05.560 --> 36:09.480
He was on the Night Train from Helsinki to Ulu in Finland.

36:10.200 --> 36:12.120
And he had 10 hours in front of him.

36:13.400 --> 36:17.240
I got a book and my newspaper, he thought.

36:17.960 --> 36:19.960
And there's a good restaurant on the train.

36:20.920 --> 36:24.920
And then I've got two weeks holiday with my Finnish friends in Ulu.

36:26.760 --> 36:29.240
There weren't many people on the train,

36:29.240 --> 36:31.960
and nobody came into Mr. Harris's carriage.

36:32.760 --> 36:34.040
He was happy about that.

36:35.160 --> 36:37.560
Most people on the train slept through the night.

36:38.280 --> 36:42.200
But Mr. Harris liked to look out of the window and to read and think.

36:43.160 --> 36:45.800
After dinner in the restaurant,

36:46.360 --> 36:51.320
Mr. Harris came back to his carriage and sat in his seat next to the window.

36:53.080 --> 36:57.560
For an hour or two, he watched the trees and lakes of Finland out of the window.

36:58.600 --> 36:59.960
Then it began to get dark.

37:00.840 --> 37:03.000
So he opened his book and began to read.

37:05.320 --> 37:08.920
At midnight, the train stopped at the small station of Otova.

37:10.040 --> 37:11.720
Mr. Harris looked out of the window.

37:12.520 --> 37:13.640
But he saw nobody.

37:15.160 --> 37:18.840
The train moved away from the station into the black night again.

37:20.440 --> 37:25.080
Then the door of Mr. Harris's carriage opened and two people came in.

37:25.880 --> 37:27.720
A young man and a young woman.

37:28.920 --> 37:30.440
The young woman was angry.

37:31.400 --> 37:33.800
She closed the door and shouted at the man.

37:34.760 --> 37:37.480
Carl, you can't do this to me.

37:38.520 --> 37:41.480
The young man laughed loudly and sat down.

37:43.480 --> 37:46.360
Mr. Harris was a small, quiet man.

37:47.160 --> 37:50.360
He wore quiet clothes and he had a quiet voice.

37:51.400 --> 37:56.600
He did not like noisy people and loud voices, so he was not pleased.

37:57.800 --> 38:01.160
Young people are always noisy, he thought.

38:01.960 --> 38:03.960
Why can't they talk quietly?

38:05.880 --> 38:08.280
He put his book down and closed his eyes.

38:09.240 --> 38:13.560
But he could not sleep because the two young people didn't stop talking.

38:15.160 --> 38:18.520
The young woman sat down and said in a quieter voice,

38:19.560 --> 38:22.920
Carl, you're my brother and I love you.

38:23.560 --> 38:25.160
But please listen to me.

38:25.960 --> 38:28.200
You can't take my diamond necklace.

38:29.080 --> 38:31.160
Give it back to me now, please.

38:32.680 --> 38:33.720
Carl smiled.

38:34.600 --> 38:36.600
No, Elena, he said.

38:37.240 --> 38:42.440
I'm going back to Russia soon and I'm taking your diamonds with me.

38:43.800 --> 38:46.440
He took off his hat and put it on the seat.

38:47.160 --> 38:48.360
Elena, listen.

38:49.240 --> 38:53.880
You have a rich husband, but I have no money.

38:54.600 --> 38:55.480
I have nothing.

38:56.200 --> 38:58.040
How can I live without money?

38:59.080 --> 39:03.000
You can't give me money, so I need your diamonds, little sister.

39:04.520 --> 39:06.600
Mr. Harris looked at the young woman.

39:07.480 --> 39:10.280
She was small with black hair and dark eyes.

39:11.320 --> 39:13.080
Her face was white and afraid.

39:14.520 --> 39:17.080
Mr. Harris began to feel sorry for Elena.

39:18.120 --> 39:20.440
She and her brother didn't look at him once.

39:21.640 --> 39:23.880
Can't they see me, he thought.

39:25.480 --> 39:27.480
Carl, Elena said.

39:28.280 --> 39:32.760
Her voice was very quiet now and Mr. Harris listened carefully.

39:34.120 --> 39:40.440
You came to dinner at our house tonight and you went to my room and took my diamond necklace.

39:41.320 --> 39:43.000
How could you do that to me?

39:44.040 --> 39:46.040
My husband gave the diamonds to me.

39:47.160 --> 39:49.400
They were his mother's diamonds before that.

39:50.120 --> 39:54.280
He's going to be very, very angry and I'm afraid of him.

39:55.560 --> 39:56.600
Her brother laughed.

39:57.240 --> 40:02.440
He put his hand in his pocket, then took it out again and opened it slowly.

40:03.720 --> 40:06.520
The diamond necklace in his hand was very beautiful.

40:07.400 --> 40:09.000
Mr. Harris stared at it.

40:10.280 --> 40:14.440
For a minute or two nobody moved and it was quiet in the carriage.

40:15.320 --> 40:20.600
There was only the noise of the train and it went quickly on through the dark cold night.

40:22.600 --> 40:25.880
Mr. Harris opened his book again but he didn't read it.

40:26.520 --> 40:31.000
He watched Carl's face with its hungry eyes and its cold smile.

40:31.800 --> 40:36.440
What beautiful, beautiful diamonds, Carl said.

40:37.160 --> 40:39.000
I can get a lot of money for these.

40:40.280 --> 40:41.880
Give them back to me, Carl.

40:42.520 --> 40:43.560
Elena whispered.

40:44.120 --> 40:45.880
My husband's going to kill me.

40:46.920 --> 40:47.880
You're my brother.

40:48.440 --> 40:49.640
Please help me.

40:50.200 --> 40:50.760
Please.

40:51.960 --> 40:55.640
Carl laughed again and Mr. Harris wanted to hit him.

40:56.680 --> 40:58.520
Go home, little sister.

40:59.160 --> 41:02.760
Carl said, I'm not going to give the diamonds back to you.

41:03.560 --> 41:05.800
Go home to your angry husband.

41:07.160 --> 41:10.120
Suddenly there was a knife in the young woman's hand.

41:10.840 --> 41:12.440
A long, bright knife.

41:13.480 --> 41:15.720
Mr. Harris watched with his mouth open.

41:16.520 --> 41:17.960
He couldn't speak or move.

41:19.240 --> 41:22.200
Give the diamonds back to me, Elena cried.

41:22.760 --> 41:24.040
Or I'm going to kill you.

41:25.000 --> 41:26.920
Her hand on the knife was white.

41:27.880 --> 41:29.560
Carl laughed and laughed.

41:30.120 --> 41:31.320
What a sister.

41:31.880 --> 41:35.480
He said, what a kind, sweet sister.

41:36.360 --> 41:39.160
No, they're my diamonds now.

41:40.120 --> 41:42.520
Put your knife away, little sister.

41:44.040 --> 41:47.880
But the knife in the white hand moved quickly, up then down.

41:48.600 --> 41:54.040
There was a long, terrible cry and Carl's body fell slowly onto the seat.

41:54.920 --> 41:57.640
The color of the seat began to change to red,

41:58.280 --> 42:01.960
and the diamond necklace fell from Carl's hand onto the floor.

42:03.560 --> 42:05.000
Elena's face was white.

42:06.040 --> 42:07.880
Oh, no, she whispered.

42:08.520 --> 42:10.440
Carl, come back.

42:11.400 --> 42:12.120
Come back.

42:13.160 --> 42:14.600
I didn't want to kill you.

42:15.800 --> 42:20.440
But Carl didn't answer, and the red blood ran slowly over the floor.

42:21.320 --> 42:27.080
Elena put her head in her hands, and again in the carriage there was a long, terrible cry.

42:28.200 --> 42:30.280
Mr. Harris's face was white, too.

42:31.080 --> 42:33.480
He opened his mouth, but he couldn't speak.

42:34.680 --> 42:37.400
He stood up and carefully moved to the door.

42:38.360 --> 42:40.120
The young woman was quiet now.

42:41.080 --> 42:43.640
She didn't move or look up at Mr. Harris.

42:44.920 --> 42:46.920
In the corridor, Mr. Harris ran.

42:47.880 --> 42:52.360
The guard was at the back of the train, and Mr. Harris got there in half a minute.

42:54.040 --> 42:56.120
Quickly, Mr. Harris said.

42:56.120 --> 42:58.280
Come quickly, an accident.

42:59.080 --> 42:59.880
A young woman.

43:00.520 --> 43:01.160
Oh, dear.

43:01.800 --> 43:04.280
Her brother is... his dead.

43:05.640 --> 43:08.600
The guard ran with Mr. Harris back to the carriage.

43:09.400 --> 43:12.040
Mr. Harris opened the door, and they went inside.

43:13.720 --> 43:15.960
There was no dead body of a young man.

43:17.000 --> 43:23.000
There was no young woman, no blood, no knife, no diamond necklace.

43:24.040 --> 43:26.920
Only Mr. Harris's bags and his hat and coat.

43:28.200 --> 43:32.120
The guard looked at Mr. Harris, and Mr. Harris looked at him.

43:33.480 --> 43:37.400
But Mr. Harris began, but they were here.

43:38.360 --> 43:39.240
I saw them.

43:40.120 --> 43:44.520
She, the young woman, she had a knife, and she...

43:45.320 --> 43:46.600
she killed her brother.

43:47.800 --> 43:49.480
A knife, you say?

43:50.040 --> 43:51.400
The guard asked.

43:51.400 --> 43:53.640
Yes, Mr. Harris said quickly.

43:54.200 --> 43:58.200
A long knife, and her brother took her diamonds, so she...

43:59.080 --> 44:02.680
Ah! Diamonds, the guard said.

44:03.800 --> 44:06.200
Was the young woman's name Elena?

44:06.840 --> 44:07.400
He asked.

44:08.360 --> 44:10.840
Yes, it was, Mr. Harris said.

44:11.880 --> 44:12.920
How do you know that?

44:13.880 --> 44:16.200
Do you... do you know her?

44:17.560 --> 44:22.440
Yes, and no, the guard said slowly.

44:23.640 --> 44:26.760
He thought for a minute, then looked at Mr. Harris.

44:28.440 --> 44:31.640
Elena de Saronelli, he said.

44:32.520 --> 44:34.840
She had dark eyes and black hair.

44:35.800 --> 44:36.760
Very beautiful.

44:37.720 --> 44:40.200
She was half Italian, half Finnish.

44:41.080 --> 44:42.840
Her brother was a half brother.

44:43.720 --> 44:47.800
They had the same father, but his mother was Russian, I think.

44:48.840 --> 44:49.240
Was?

44:50.280 --> 44:50.760
Had?

44:51.880 --> 44:54.120
Mr. Harris stared at the guard.

44:55.080 --> 44:55.880
But she...

44:56.840 --> 44:59.000
Elena, she's alive.

44:59.880 --> 45:00.840
And where is she?

45:01.720 --> 45:03.960
Oh no, said the guard.

45:04.520 --> 45:08.440
Elena de Saronelli died about 80 years ago.

45:09.320 --> 45:14.920
After she killed her brother with a knife, she jumped off the train and died at once.

45:15.960 --> 45:17.640
It was near here, I think.

45:18.440 --> 45:20.280
He looked out of the window into the night.

45:21.880 --> 45:24.120
Mr. Harris' face was very white again.

45:25.480 --> 45:28.120
80 years ago, he whispered.

45:28.920 --> 45:29.880
What are you saying?

45:31.400 --> 45:32.680
Was she and her brother?

45:33.960 --> 45:35.080
But I saw them.

45:36.040 --> 45:37.960
Yes, that's right.

45:38.440 --> 45:42.760
The guard said, you saw them, but they're not alive.

45:43.480 --> 45:44.520
They're ghosts.

45:45.560 --> 45:49.000
They often come on the night train at this time in September.

45:50.040 --> 45:54.040
I never see them, but somebody saw them last year.

45:54.840 --> 45:56.200
A man and his wife.

45:57.080 --> 45:58.840
They were very unhappy about it.

45:59.720 --> 46:00.680
But what can I do?

46:01.560 --> 46:04.920
I can't stop Elena and Carl coming on the train.

46:05.800 --> 46:08.520
The guard looked at Mr. Harris' white face.

46:09.240 --> 46:11.240
You need a drink, he said.

46:12.040 --> 46:13.960
Come and have a vodka with me.

46:15.080 --> 46:19.640
Mr. Harris didn't usually drink vodka, but he felt afraid.

46:20.280 --> 46:27.320
When he closed his eyes, he could see again Elena's long knife and could hear her terrible cry.

46:27.960 --> 46:31.000
So he went with the guard to the back of the train.

46:31.080 --> 46:34.040
After the vodka, Mr. Harris felt better.

46:35.080 --> 46:38.360
He didn't want to sleep, and the guard was happy to talk.

46:39.320 --> 46:43.400
So Mr. Harris stayed with the guard and didn't go back to his carriage.

46:44.120 --> 46:46.360
Yes, the guard said.

46:46.760 --> 46:48.520
It's a famous story.

46:49.720 --> 46:51.560
I don't remember it all.

46:52.520 --> 46:55.160
It happened a long time ago, of course.

46:56.200 --> 47:00.840
Elena's father, who was a father of his father, was a father of his father.

47:01.000 --> 47:03.560
Was a famous man here in Finland.

47:04.600 --> 47:10.520
He was very rich once, but he had three or four wives and about eight children.

47:11.480 --> 47:16.040
And he liked the good things of life, so there wasn't much money for the children.

47:17.160 --> 47:21.640
Carl, the oldest son, was a bad man, people say.

47:22.680 --> 47:26.840
He wanted an easy life, and money in his hand all the time.

47:26.840 --> 47:34.360
The train hurried on to Ulu through the Black Knight, and the guard drank some more vodka.

47:35.560 --> 47:42.200
Now Elena, he said, she didn't have an easy life with those three difficult men,

47:42.920 --> 47:45.880
her father, her brother, her husband.

47:46.920 --> 47:54.600
One year, she visited her mother's family in Italy, and there she met her husband, Disaronelli.

47:54.680 --> 47:59.400
Disaronelli, he was rich, but he wasn't a kind man.

48:00.360 --> 48:04.360
They came back to Finland, and Carl often visited their house.

48:05.400 --> 48:08.280
He wanted money from his sister's rich husband.

48:09.400 --> 48:13.000
Elena loved her brother and gave him some money,

48:13.720 --> 48:18.360
but Disaronelli didn't like Carl and was angry with Elena.

48:19.640 --> 48:23.000
He stopped giving her money, and after that,

48:23.800 --> 48:26.920
well, you know the story now.

48:28.360 --> 48:33.080
Yes, Mr. Harris said, poor, unhappy Elena.

48:35.320 --> 48:38.840
Mr. Harris stayed with his friends in Ulu for two weeks.

48:39.960 --> 48:43.560
They were quiet weeks, and Mr. Harris had a good holiday.

48:45.080 --> 48:47.480
But he took the bus back to Helsinki.

48:48.520 --> 48:51.720
The bus was slow, and there were a lot of people on it,

48:52.600 --> 48:54.440
but Mr. Harris was very happy.

48:55.720 --> 49:00.040
He didn't want to take the night train across Finland again.

